qa.gt:
I hear how unsettling the word “leukemia” feels, especially when you’re juggling a demanding job and a new diagnosis—your anxiety is understandable.  

Most TKIs, like imatinib, nilotinib, and bosutinib, need a mildly acidic stomach for absorption. PPIs can lower acidity and reduce drug levels, so they’re usually avoided or timed carefully.  

If you need a PPI for reflux, ask your oncologist about taking it at least 4 hours before or after the TKI, or consider an H2 blocker instead. Calcium, magnesium, iron, and high‑dose vitamin C can chelate the drug;
